[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(14-16) Apparently nine sons of Beriah. But (1) in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Chronicles 8:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the LXX. reads ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὁ ἀδελφὸς αὐτοῦ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " instead of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ahio.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " With different vowels the Hebrew term would mean this. (2) All the other names in this list are connected by the conjunctive particle. It is therefore likely that this was once the case with Shashak. (3) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Chronicles 8:14-27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " give five groups of Benjamite clans—viz., the sons of Beriah, the sons of Elpaal, the sons of Shimhi, the sons of Shashak, and the sons of Jeroham, all dwelling in Jerusalem. Apparently, their eponymous heads are named in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Chronicles 8:13-14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—viz., Beriah (Elpaal? omitted by accident), Shema (the same as Shimhi; there is no ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "h",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in the Heb.), Shashak, and Jeremoth (probably the same as Jeroham).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "If this combination hold, the text of 1Chronicles 8:14 may be thus restored: “And Elpaal his brother, and Shashak and Jeroham.” Elpaal will then be brother of Beriah (1Chronicles 8:13), and perhaps son of Elpaal (1Chronicles 8:12). Shashak and Jeremoth-Jeroham, and the six following names, are sons of Beriah.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "If this combination hold, the text of ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 8:14",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " may be thus restored: “And Elpaal his brother, and Shashak and Jeroham.” Elpaal will then be brother of Beriah (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 8:13",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "), and perhaps son of Elpaal (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 8:12",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). Shashak and Jeremoth-Jeroham, and the six following names, are sons of Beriah.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "8:1-40 Genealogies. - Here is a larger list of Benjamin's tribe. We may suppose that many things in these genealogies, which to us seem difficult, abrupt, and perplexed, were plain and easy at that time, and fully answered the intention for which they were published. Many great and mighty nations then were in being upon earth, and many illustrious men, whose names are now wholly forgotten; while the names of multitudes of the Israel of God are here kept in everlasting remembrance. The memory of the just is blessed.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
